revision.text:
In [[mathematics]], a '''Moishezon manifold''' {{mvar|M}} is a compact [[complex manifold]] such that the [[field (mathematics)|field]] of [[meromorphic function]]s on each component {{mvar|M}} has [[transcendence degree]] equal the [[complex dimension]] of the component:

:<math>\dim_\mathbf{C}M=a(M)=\operatorname{tr.deg.}_\mathbf{C}\mathbf{C}(M).</math>

Complex [[algebraic variety|algebraic varieties]] have this property, but the converse is not true: [[Hironaka's example]] gives a smooth 3-dimensional Moishezon manifold that is not an algebraic variety or [[scheme (mathematics)|scheme]].  {{harvs|txt|last=Moishezon|year=1966|loc=Chapter I, Theorem 11|authorlink=Boris Moishezon}} showed that a Moishezon manifold is a [[projective algebraic variety]] if and only if it admits a [[Kähler metric]]. {{harvtxt|Artin|1970}} showed that any Moishezon manifold carries an [[algebraic space]] structure; more precisely, the category of Moishezon spaces (similar to Moishezon manifolds, but are allowed to have singularities) is equivalent with the category of algebraic spaces that are proper over {{math|Spec('''C''')}}.

==References==
* {{Citation | last=Artin | first1=M. |authorlink=Michael Artin| title=Algebraization of formal moduli, II. Existence of modification | year=1970 | journal=Ann. of Math. | volume=91 | pages=88–135|jstor=1970602|doi=10.2307/1970602}}
* {{Citation| last=Moishezon | first1=B.G. | title=On n-dimensional compact varieties with n algebraically independent meromorphic functions, I, II and III | year=1966 | journal=Izv. Akad. Nauk SSSR Ser. Mat. | volume=30 | pages=133–174 345–386 621–656}} English translation. AMS Translation Ser. 2, 63 51-177
*{{citation|first=B. |last=Moishezon|chapter=Algebraic varieties and compact complex spaces|title= Proc. Internat. Congress Mathematicians (Nice, 1970) |volume= 2 |publisher= Gauthier-Villars |year=1971|pages=643–648 |mr=0425189|url=http://ada00.math.uni-bielefeld.de/ICM/ICM1970.2/}}

