{{Infobox hotel | hotel_name = Rodd Charlottetown | image = Rodd Charlottetown 2012.jpg | image_width = | caption = The Hotel Charlottetown seen in October 2012. | pushpin_map = | location = {{nowrap|[[Charlottetown]], [[Prince Edward Island]]}} | address = 75 Kent Street | chain = Rodd Hotels & Resorts | coordinates = {{coord|46|14|5|N|63|7|51|W|region:CA-PE|display=inline,title}} | opening_date = 1931
| diamonds = | closing_date = | developer = | architect = | operator = Rodd Hotels and Resorts | owner = Rodd Hotels and Resorts | number_of_restaurants = Chambers Restaurant & Bar | number_of_rooms = 115 | number_of_suites = 7 | floor_area = | floors = 5 | parking = yes | website = {{URL|http://www.roddvacations.com/rodd-charlottetown}} | footnotes = <ref name="Emporis">{{Emporis|383153}}</ref><ref name=Ferries>{{cite web|title=Rodd Charlottetown|url=http://www.ferries.ca/accommodations/rodd-charlottetown/|publisher=Northumberland Ferries Limited and Bay Ferries Limited|accessdate=25 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307092857/http://www.ferries.ca/accommodations/rodd-charlottetown/|archive-date=7 March 2013|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="Canada Select">{{cite web|title=Rodd Charlottetown|url=http://www.canadaselect.com/prince-edward-island/charlottetown/rodd-charlottetown-rodd-signature-hotel|publisher=Canada Select|accessdate=25 June 2013}}</ref> }} The '''Hotel Charlottetown''' was a hotel built in 1931 in [[Charlottetown]], [[Prince Edward Island]] by the [[Canadian National Railway]] (through their lodging division, [[Canadian National Hotels]]).
Its most notable guests were Her Majesty [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]] who stayed at the hotel during Prince Edward Island's centennial [[Canadian Confederation|Confederation]] celebrations in July 1973.
[[Canadian National Hotels]] sold the property to [[Rodd Hotels and Resorts]] in the early 1980s. Since then, the hotel has operated as the '''Rodd Charlottetown''', also known informally as the '''Charlottetown Hotel'''. Rodd funded a renovation and restoration project in 1999.
