{{advert|date=May 2016}} {{Infobox hotel | hotel_name = Jasper Park Lodge | image = Jasper Park Lodge.jpg | image_size = 250 | caption = Jasper Park Lodge, Alberta, Canada | location = [[Jasper, Alberta]], Canada | coordinates = {{coord|52|53|10|N|118|03|25|W|region:CA-AB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | opening_date = 1922
| diamonds = | closing_date = | developer = | operator = [[Fairmont Hotels and Resorts]] | owner = [[Ontario Municipal Employees Retirement System]]<ref>http://www.omers.com/Real_estate/Portfolio_overview_-_Oxford_Properties.htm</ref> | number_of_restaurants = 5 | number_of_rooms = 446 | number_of_suites = | floor_area = | floors = 1 | parking = | website = [http://www.fairmont.com/jasper/ www.fairmont.com/jasper] | footnotes = }}
The '''Jasper Park Lodge''' opened in 1922<ref>[http://www.fairmont.com/jasper/hotelhistory/ Fairmont Jasper Park Lodge - Hotel History]</ref> in [[Jasper, Alberta|Jasper]], [[Alberta]], Canada and is situated on the shores of [[Lac Beauvert]].
== History == The lodge had first been established in 1915 as a "Tent City," in association with the [[Grand Trunk Pacific Railway]], but by the 1920s the property was under the management of [[Canadian National Hotels]]. Eight bungalows were constructed in 1921, and work began on additional cabins and a main lodge building two years later. The main building, reputed to be the largest single-level log structure in the world, was destroyed by fire in 1952;<ref name=1952fire>{{cite news | url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/July+1952+Blaze+destroys+Jasper+Park+Lodge/6937026/story.html | title= July 15, 1952: Blaze destroys Jasper Park Lodge | newspaper=[[Edmonton Journal]] | publisher=[[Postmedia Network]] | date=2012-07-15 | accessdate=2012-07-15}}</ref> it was replaced by the current lodge, which was completed the following year. Jasper Park Lodge was sold to [[Canadian Pacific Hotels]] in 1988 and now operates as '''Fairmont Jasper Park Lodge'''. In 2006, it was purchased by [[Oxford Properties]], the real estate investment arm of [[OMERS|Ontario Municipal Employees Retirement System (OMERS)]], but is operated by [[Fairmont Hotels]].<ref>[http://www2.canada.com/vancouversun/news/business/story.html?id=f7504619-d278-4344-bfa9-64a79c223208 Constantineau, Bruce. "Pension plan buys 7 Fairmont hotels for about $1.5b,"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301011734/http://www2.canada.com/vancouversun/news/business/story.html?id=f7504619-d278-4344-bfa9-64a79c223208 |date=2012-03-01 }}, Vancouver Sun. October 3, 2006.</ref>
Many celebrities have stayed, including [[Bing Crosby]] and [[Marilyn Monroe]]. It is also a favoured spot of the Royal Family, with visits from King [[George VI]] and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]] in 1939 and Her Majesty [[Queen Elizabeth II]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] in 2005.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}
A $6.7 million Fairmont spa was added to the Lodge in fall 2010. In 2015-16, a $16 million renovation to all rooms (Fairmont, Deluxe, Junior Suites and Lakefront Suites) was completed to modernize the decor. ORSO Trattoria, the hotel's first Italian restaurant, was also added to the dining options, which includes The Nook Chophouse, Emerald Lounge & Patio, Thompson's Terrace (golf course) and Oka Sushi.
