{{automatic taxobox |image = Acantholimon glumaceum.jpg |taxon = Acantholimon |authority = [[Pierre Edmond Boissier|Boiss.]] |subdivision_ranks = Species |subdivision = See text }}
'''''Acantholimon''''' ('''prickly thrift''') is a [[genus]] of small [[flowering plants]] within the plumbago or leadwort family, [[Plumbaginaceae]]. They are distributed from southeastern [[Europe]] to central [[Asia]] and also in [[South America]], but also cultivated elsewhere in [[rock garden]]s.
==Form== The evergreen [[subshrub]]s are generally cushion to mat-forming, with densely tufted shoots bearing mostly awl (long, pointed spike) to needle or grass-like, prickle to spine-tipped hard-textured leaves. They have shortish, simple or branched flower stems which can be loose or dense. The summer-borne flowers are composed of a funnel-shaped [[Calyx (flower)|calyx]], usually with a flared membranous margin, and five spreading petals.<ref name=alpine>{{cite web| title=Iris willmottiana | year=2001| url=http://encyclopaedia.alpinegardensociety.net/plants/Acantholimon | publisher=encyclopaedia.alpinegardensociety.net | accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref>
==Species== There are over 400 species.<ref>{{cite web |title=Results |url=http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl1.1/search?q=Acantholimon |publisher=theplantlist.org ([[The Plant List]])|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref>
Selected species of ''Acantholimon'' include: *''[[Acantholimon albertii]]'' *''[[Acantholimon avenaceum]]'' *''[[Acantholimon gabrieljaniae]]'' *''[[Acantholimon glumaceum]]'' *''[[Acantholimon goeksunicum]]'' *''[[Acantholimon karamanicum]]'' *''[[Acantholimon koeycegizicum]]'' *''[[Acantholimon libanoticum]]'' *''[[Acantholimon vedicum]]'' *''[[Acantholimon venustum]]''
[[File:Acantholimon sp. S.jpg|left|thumb|''Acantholimon sp.'']] {{clear|left}}
