{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{BLP sources|date=February 2012}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Emmanuel Olisadebe | image = Emmanuel Olisadebe.jpg | image_size = 200 | caption = Olisadebe with [[Henan Construction]] in 2009 | fullname = | height = 1.80 m | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1978|12|22}} | birth_place = [[Warri, Nigeria]] | currentclub = | clubnumber = | position = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]] | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = 1995–1997 | years2 = 1997–2001 | years3 = 2001–2005 | years4 = 2005–2006 | years5 = 2006–2007 | years6 = 2007–2008 | years7 = 2008–2010 | years8 = 2010–2011 | years9 = 2011–2012 | years10 = 2011–2012 | clubs1 = [[Jasper United]] | clubs2 = [[Polonia Warsaw]] | clubs3 = [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]] | clubs4 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] | clubs5 = [[Skoda Xanthi]] | clubs6 = [[APOP Kinyras Peyias FC|APOP Kinyras Peyias]] | clubs7 = [[Henan Construction F.C.|Henan Construction]] | clubs10 = [[Veria F.C.|Veria]] | caps1 = 40 | caps2 = 66 | caps3 = 74 | caps4 = 2 | caps5 = 5 | caps6 = 17 | caps7 = 63 | caps9 = 0 | caps10 = 9 | goals1 = 20 | goals2 = 20 | goals3 = 24 | goals4 = 0 | goals5 = 0 | goals6 = 6 | goals7 = 24 | goals9 = 0 | goals10 = 1 | totalcaps = 276 | totalgoals = 95 | nationalyears1 = 2000–2004 | nationalteam1 = [[Polish national football team|Poland]] | nationalcaps1 = 25 | nationalgoals1 = 11 | pcupdate = | ntupdate = }}
'''Emmanuel Olisadebe''' ({{IPA-pl|ɛmaˈnuɛl olisaˈdɛbɛ}}; born 22 December 1978) is a retired Polish [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]].
He began his career with [[Jasper United]], going on to have a successful career with [[Polonia Warsaw]] where in 2000 he won the [[Ekstraklasa]], [[Ekstraklasa Cup]] and [[Polish SuperCup]]. He also played in Greece, Cyprus, England and China.
Born in Nigeria, he attracted the attention of the [[Poland national football team|Polish national team]] after he was eligible for Polish citizenship. He scored 11 international goals in 25 caps between 2000 and 2004, and participated in the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]].
==Club career==
===Polonia Warsaw=== Olisadebe began playing for [[Polonia Warsaw]] during the [[1997–98 Ekstraklasa]] season where in his first season he played in 13 league games.<ref name="national-football-teams.com">{{NFT player|id=5226|accessdate=}}</ref> During his time in the Polish capital he helped them secure their first championship title in 50 years in the [[1999–2000 Ekstraklasa|1999–2000 season]], scoring 12 goals in the process. He also won the League Cup and the Super Cup that season.
===Panathinaikos=== Olisadebe moved to [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] where he scored 24 goals in 74 matches.<ref name="national-football-teams.com"/> In 2004, he helped the club win the title for the first time in 7 years by scoring all the winning goals in the last three of four games of [[2003-04 Alpha Ethniki|the championship]]. He also won [[2003-04 Greek Cup|the cup that year]], making it a [[Double (association football)|double]]. However, during his time at Panathinaikos he suffered an injury that required surgery in Greece.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}}
===Portsmouth=== On 4 January 2006, he joined [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] until the end of the [[2005–06 Portsmouth F.C. season|2005–06 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/4582378.stm|title=Portsmouth seal Olisadebe swoop|publisher=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> He made his debut ten days later, replacing [[Richard Hughes (footballer)|Richard Hughes]] after 61 minutes of an eventual 0–1 [[Premier League]] defeat to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] at [[Fratton Park]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Portsmouth 0-1 Everton|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4590274.stm|accessdate=27 May 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=14 January 2006}}</ref> A week later he made his only other appearance for the club, playing the final 37 minutes of a 0–5 defeat at [[Birmingham City]], this time in place of [[Vincent Péricard]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Birmingham 5-0 Portsmouth|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4612190.stm|accessdate=27 May 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=21 January 2006}}</ref>
His contract was terminated after 4 months, at which point he travelled to [[Skoda Xanthi F.C.|Skoda Xanthi]], where he wasn't given a chance to play.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}}
===APOP Kinyras Peyias=== He then featured for [[APOP Kinyras Peyia FC]] where he played in the 2007–08 season where he played in 17 games scoring 6 goals.<ref name="national-football-teams.com"/>
===Henan Construction=== In 2008, he was offered a deal with [[Chinese Super League]] club [[Henan Construction F.C.|Henan Construction]]. In his second match with Henan, the third round of 2008 Chinese Super League against [[Liaoning Hongyun|Liaoning]], he scored 2 goals. In first season at Henan he scored 12 goals in 26 games in the Chinese super league.
On 27 September, Olisadebe scored the opening goal for Henan in a 2–0 win over [[Shanghai Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]] to regain lead in the league less than ten minutes before injuring his knee. Initial diagnosis showed that he had torn his [[cruciate ligament]] of the left knee, and the injury could end his entire football career.<ref>{{cite web| title = 奥贝初步诊断十字韧带断裂 赛季报销恐将提前退役| publisher= sina.com.cn| url = http://sports.sina.com.cn/j/2009-09-27/23104608263.shtml| accessdate = 28 September 2009}}</ref> Further results confirmed that he injured his [[patellar ligament]] and would only miss the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web| title = 奥贝确诊髌腱韧带脱落 缺席本赛季不危及职业生涯| publisher= sina.com.cn| url = http://sports.sina.com.cn/j/2009-09-28/18324609795.shtml| accessdate = 29 September 2009}}</ref> He was nominated for the MVP awards two years consecutively only to be 2nd in both occasions.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}} Due to his performance he has been granted by the government of Henan province citizenship.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}}
==International career== Though Nigerian by birth, Olisadebe became a Polish citizen in 2000 and was selected by the [[Poland national football team|Poland national team]]. He scored eight goals in ten [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualification matches]] as coach [[Jerzy Engel]]'s team reached the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]], their first since [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]], gaining one vote for [[2001 FIFA World Player of the Year]]. He netted their second of three goals in a victory over [[Norway national football team|Norway]] on 1 September which confirmed qualification.<ref>{{cite news|title=The strange case of Emmanuel Olisadebe|url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/wsc-daily/1016-July-2011/7396-the-strange-case-of-emmanuel-olisadebe|accessdate=27 May 2015|work=[[When Saturday Comes]]|date=13 July 2011}}</ref>
Olisadebe scored Poland's first goal of their [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] campaign in a 3–1 victory against the [[USMNT|United States]] in [[Daejeon]] in the last group match,<ref>{{cite news|title=American dream lives on|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/matches_wallchart/poland_v_usa/default.stm|accessdate=27 May 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=14 June 2002}}</ref> however Poland did not progress to the second round and Olisadebe would not score again for Poland.
