{{Infobox UK place | country = England | coordinates = {{coord|52.87262|0.62547|display=inline,title}} | os_grid_reference = TF768338 | official_name = Bircham Newton | population = | area_total_km2 = | shire_district = [[King's Lynn and West Norfolk]] | shire_county = [[Norfolk]] | region = East of England | civil_parish = [[Bircham]] | constituency_westminster = | postcode_district = PE31 | postcode_area = PE | post_town = [[King's Lynn]] | dial_code = | london_distance = | hide_services = true |static_image = All Saints, Bircham Newton, Norfolk - geograph.org.uk - 310333.jpg |static_image_width = 240px |static_image_caption= All Saints, Bircham Newton }}
'''Bircham Newton''' is the smallest of the three villages that make up the [[civil parish]] of [[Bircham]] , in the west of the [[England|English]] county of [[Norfolk]]. The village is located about 1&nbsp;km north of the larger village of [[Great Bircham]], 20&nbsp;km north-east of the town of [[King's Lynn]], and 60&nbsp;km north-west of the city of [[Norwich]].{{ref|osexp1}}
Bircham Newton gave its name to an airfield, [[RAF Bircham Newton]], that was in use through [[World War II]] and into the 1960s. Today the airfield is the home of the [[Construction Industry Training Board]] (now [[ConstructionSkills]]).
==References== *{{note|osexp1}} Ordnance Survey (2002). ''OS Explorer Map 250 - Norfolk Coast West''. {{ISBN|0-319-21886-4}}.
